Project: Kubernetes-based Microservices Deployment for an E-commerce Application

Answer:
In my recent project, we migrated a traditional 3-tier monolithic application into a microservices architecture and deployed it using Kubernetes.
The application consisted of multiple services like frontend, cart, product, and payment services. Each service was containerized using Docker and deployed as independent microservices.
My main responsibility was to create and manage Kubernetes clusters, deploy applications using YAML manifests and kubectl, and ensure high availability by running multiple replicas for critical services like payment and frontend.
I also managed source code using Git, where different development teams worked on separate microservices.
For monitoring, we implemented Prometheus and Grafana to track application health and cluster performance.
Additionally, I handled troubleshooting tasks like checking pod logs, resolving deployment issues, and redeploying services when required. We were also planning to automate deployments using Jenkins to implement CI/CD pipelines.
Overall, this architecture improved application scalability, reduced downtime, and made deployments easier compared to the earlier monolithic setup.
